# Auto-create Jira stories for new features

When you implement a **new user-facing feature or a new function/capability** in this
repo, create a corresponding **Story** in Jira using the Atlassian MCP server
(`atlassian`). Do this after the change is written, then report the created issue key/URL.

## When to create a story
- A new feature, page, endpoint, workstream, or meaningful capability is added.
- Do **NOT** create a story for: bug fixes, refactors, formatting, comments, tests,
  docs-only edits, or dependency bumps. (Mention you skipped it.)
- If unsure whether something qualifies, ask the user before creating.

## Before creating — avoid duplicates
1. Search Jira for an existing matching story (by summary/keywords) first.
2. If a close match exists, comment on / link to it instead of creating a duplicate.

## Story content (use this template)
- **Project**: `ClearCaseIQ` (project key `CP`).
- **Issue type**: Story.
- **Summary**: short imperative title of the feature (e.g., "Add SOL email reminders").
- **Description** (use this body):
  - `As a <role>, I want <capability> so that <benefit>.`
  - `Acceptance Criteria:` 2–4 bullet points describing observable behavior.
  - `Source:` the key files/paths changed.
- **Parent/Epic**: link to the most relevant existing epic (Claimant Intake, Attorney
  Dashboard & Workstreams, Matching & Routing, etc.) when one fits.
- **Labels**: a domain label (e.g., `intake`, `attorney`, `routing`) plus `auto-created`.

## After creating
- Print the new issue key and URL.
- If MCP isn't connected/authenticated, tell the user to authenticate the `atlassian`
  MCP server instead of silently skipping.
